<div class="prose dark:prose-invert my-6">
  <p>Rails let's you get moving quickly with scaffolds. Under the hood, files and code are generated to remove the repetative nature of setting up new logic. The <%= theme_name.humanize %> theme provides some sensible defaults to make design work quickly for you as well.</p>

  <p>When you install Rails UI the installer adds a generator configuration to your app's <%= code "config/application.rb" %> file </p>
</div>

<div class="not-prose w-full">
<% content_for :ruby, flush: true do %>
module <%= theme_name.humanize %>
  class Application < Rails::Application
    config.generators do |g|
      g.template_engine :railsui
      # more generator stuff
    end
  end
end
<% end %>
<%= render_snippet active_tab: "ruby", ruby_filename: "application.rb" %>
</div>

<div class="prose dark:prose-invert my-6">
  <p>If you'd prefer the default scaffolding templates, remove the line <%= code("g.template_engine :railsui") %> from your <%= code("application.rb") %> file as shown in the example above.</p>
</div>

<%= render callout do %>
  <p>For the sake of example it's assumed we'll generate a scaffold with a <%= code("Post") %> model. Substitute your own resource when referring to the snippets below.</p>
<% end %>

<%= render "railsui/themes/#{Railsui.config.theme.downcase}/scaffolds/index" %>
<%= render "railsui/themes/#{Railsui.config.theme.downcase}/scaffolds/show" %>
<%= render "railsui/themes/#{Railsui.config.theme.downcase}/scaffolds/new" %>
<%= render "railsui/themes/#{Railsui.config.theme.downcase}/scaffolds/edit" %>
<%= render "railsui/themes/#{Railsui.config.theme.downcase}/scaffolds/partial" %>

